Date: 31 Aug 2001 11:01 AM
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://news.cnet.com/investor/news/newsitem/0-9900-1028-7024544-0.html>

Baxter recalls certain dialyzers after deaths in Spain
------------------------------------------------------
U.S. medical device firm Baxter International Inc. said on Friday that it
has recalled 2 batches of dialysis products after 6 patients at a health
center in Spain died while having kidney dialysis treatment.
Tanya Tyska, spokeswoman for Deerfield, Illinois-based Baxter, told Reuters
that the patients who died in Valencia, Spain were receiving treatment
using different dialysis products and equipment, some of which were
manufactured by Baxter.
"Initial studies conducted by Baxter showed no malfunction of its products,
and have not revealed any evidence linking the Baxter product to the
unfortunate deaths of these patients. However, as a precautionary measure,
we have initiated a voluntary recall of 2 batches of the A-18 dialyzers,
one of the dialysis products used by that center," Tyska said.
"We are working with the hospital and the medical authorities to help
clarify the facts. In the meantime, we will do everything we can to assist
the center an ensure patients' safety and continuity of care," she added.
