[3]
Date: 22 Sept. 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Financial Times [edited]
<http://globalarchive.ft.com/globalarchive/article.html?id=010922007957>

Spanish health ministry believes first control detected leaks in filters
linked to deaths
-----------------------------
The Spanish health ministry is investigating the possibility that the
filters linked to the deaths of 12 patients after dialysis sessions in
Valencia, Madrid and Barcelona did not pass a first quality control.
Health inspectors have informed the Valencian regional government that they
were surprised that the supplier of the filters, US company Baxter, only
distributed 460 units of the lot linked to the deaths, when other lots
include 10 000 units. According to a report by the Valencian regional
government, the health ministry believes that the filters did not pass the
first control, though they did pass other controls after leaks were sealed.
The filters were then distributed by Baxter.
